version: 1
display_name: VCFE-9X-000200 - The ESX host must automatically stop shell services after ten minutes.
global_description: |-
  When the ESX Shell or Secure Shell (SSH) services are enabled on a host, they will run indefinitely. To avoid having these services left running, set the "ESXiShellTimeOut". The "ESXiShellTimeOut" defines a window of time after which the ESX Shell and SSH services will be stopped automatically.
osfinger: []  # API/proxy-managed control; not tied to a minion OS grain
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFE-9X-000200
  srg:
    - SRG-OS-000163-VMM-000700
  cci:
    - CCI-001133
  nist:
    - SC-10
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_vsphere_esx:
    type: custom
    desc: The ESX host must automatically stop shell services after ten minutes.
    control_id: VCFE-9X-000200
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Select the "UserVars.ESXiShellTimeOut" value and verify it is set to "600" or less and not "0".

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name UserVars.ESXiShellTimeOut

      If the "UserVars.ESXiShellTimeOut" setting is set to a value greater than "600" or "0", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      When the ESX Shell or Secure Shell (SSH) services are enabled on a host, they will run indefinitely. To avoid having these services left running, set the "ESXiShellTimeOut". The "ESXiShellTimeOut" defines a window of time after which the ESX Shell and SSH services will be stopped automatically.
    remediation: |-
      From the vSphere Client, go to Hosts and Clusters.

      Select the ESX Host >> Configure >> System >> Advanced System Settings.

      Click "Edit". Select the "UserVars.ESXiShellTimeOut" value and configure it to "600".

      or

      From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESX host, run the following command:

      Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name UserVars.ESXiShellTimeOut | Set-AdvancedSetting -Value 600
